00:07:26.480 --> 00:07:32.079
trends. Is it going down? Is it going up? Where is this concentration spreading to?

00:07:33.359 --> 00:07:38.799
And to do that, we use smoothing statistics, and I'll give more examples of this during the

00:07:38.799 --> 00:07:46.000
demonstration as well, both smoothing in one-dimensional time series, for example using

00:07:46.959 --> 00:07:52.480
local linear regression. We also use spatial smoothing. I think we do the groundwater

00:07:52.480 --> 00:07:59.359
elevation now, but uniquely in the industry, we use a spatial temporal smoother,

00:08:01.119 --> 00:08:08.399
which effectively, it's the way that the industry typically works, is you get a concentration contour

00:08:08.399 --> 00:08:14.559
for one round of sampling. It's another concentration contour independently to the

00:08:14.640 --> 00:08:20.720
second round that you collect this information, and so on, and so on, and so on. So in the old

00:08:20.720 --> 00:08:25.920
traditional way of doing things, you know, you would have three sort of spatial cricking models here,

00:08:26.959 --> 00:08:31.600
but glus.app does it differently, effectively does it in a one-er,

00:08:31.600 --> 00:08:37.119
right, and there are various different benefits of doing that, which is subject to the paper that I'll

00:08:37.119 --> 00:08:44.320
reference later on, one of it being data extraction efficiency, where you just get more information

00:08:44.320 --> 00:08:49.359
out for the same amount of data, one spatial temporal model, rather than having separate

00:08:49.359 --> 00:08:55.039
independent spatial. Worth pointing out that it was with the help of the University of Glasgow,

00:08:55.039 --> 00:09:00.320
the underlying methodology for the spatial temporal statistics is penalised spline,

00:09:01.520 --> 00:09:06.880
line-based methodology, and we went for this way more than anything because of the speed of

00:09:06.880 --> 00:09:12.799
