No, it doesn't. This is, we used to use a package called add-on client, but we found it

00:47:55.600 --> 00:48:03.679
kind of not particularly well supported. So I wrote a little bit of a hack to be honest here,

00:48:03.760 --> 00:48:11.360
right? If you download and do that add-in, you will see that all the code is there

00:48:12.320 --> 00:48:20.479
on how to do it, right? So the way it actually does it is it dynamically builds like a text file

00:48:22.399 --> 00:48:27.120
on the fly, which sort of saves off your different variables and all the rest of it.

00:48:27.840 --> 00:48:35.520
And then it sends that over together with the datasets as input to an R batch file.

00:48:37.120 --> 00:48:44.000
And that's kind of how it works. And that works fine because it's only one way traffic, right?

00:48:44.000 --> 00:48:51.040
And that you're just sending the data from Excel into R. If you had to do the other way around as

00:48:51.040 --> 00:48:55.040
well, then the architecture, what I'm currently using would fall flat in place.

