Yeah, that's a good question, right? I mean, in terms of, yeah, it wasn't me that actually

00:49:39.360 --> 00:49:45.600
did the first shiny version, right? We had a postdoc who was doing it on a six-month basis.

00:49:45.600 --> 00:49:52.879
He ported most of the functionality that was there before. And then I've added to it since,

00:49:52.879 --> 00:49:58.879
effectively, right? You know, key to the number one was the spatial plot, right?

00:49:58.879 --> 00:50:05.840
Having that movie of the spatial distribution and slowly exchange it through time is number one,

00:50:05.840 --> 00:50:11.520
right? And then everything effectively follows from that. That's the unique plot, right? That's

00:50:11.520 --> 00:50:18.000
the plot that was really hard to do in Excel for example, which is typically how some of the

00:50:18.000 --> 00:50:23.600
consoles used to do this in the past. You could do the well-timed series plus. You could do,

00:50:23.600 --> 00:50:27.840
you know, different overlays and the rest of it. But the spatial distribution design,

00:50:27.840 --> 00:50:36.320
that's clearly the qua, yeah? The unique selling point. I hope that makes sense.

00:50:38.479 --> 00:50:42.639
And I guess I would say convenience as well, right? Having it all there in one place,

00:50:43.360 --> 00:50:49.120
you know, in a reproducible, repeatable fashion, right? You know, the data input's always the same

00:50:49.120 --> 00:50:54.879
and you get lots of options and plotting. The same cannot be said of doing it in Excel manually,

00:50:55.439 --> 00:51:00.239
take all day for people to come up with a lattice of plots. You can do that in literally seconds.

