Sorry, they asked to be anonymous, so I don't want to just like show it up on the screen,

00:58:09.360 --> 00:58:15.919
but I can reread it. It said, I'm curious to know how they manage any confounding variables

00:58:15.919 --> 00:58:21.760
with the data provided in the open source you presented, or biased data.

00:58:22.479 --> 00:58:27.840
It's a good question. I would say, typically, we don't have any confounders.

00:58:28.800 --> 00:58:37.120
I'll go into that in a minute. In the time series plots, right, it's not like we're

00:58:38.000 --> 00:58:40.879
doing a regression of one against the other, it's all against time.

00:58:44.479 --> 00:58:48.719
When it comes to fitting the spatial plot, right, it's using splines,

00:58:49.360 --> 00:58:58.800
right, it uses a three-dimensional spline basis, and obviously these variables, by design,

00:58:58.800 --> 00:59:03.199
are not going to confound one another. The danger there is overfitting, right,

00:59:03.199 --> 00:59:09.199
more than confounding parameters, and this is where p-spline comes into its own, is that it penalises

00:59:10.719 --> 00:59:16.959
the step changes from these parameters estimated from the spline, and that's what controls the

00:59:16.959 --> 00:59:22.560
degree of complexity and balances between under and overfitting. Yeah, so

00:59:24.239 --> 00:59:29.520
confounding variables isn't really an issue for that reason, because we use spline by design,

00:59:29.520 --> 00:59:34.719
they're not confounded. Overfitting is, but it's controlled through this penalised drawing.

